Command line interfaces

Command line interfaces¶

If you are viewing this page on a computer, you are probably using a point-and-click Graphical User Interface (GUI, pronounced GOO-ee). GUI’s became mainstream with the rise of personal computers in the 1980s, but prior to that, programmers did most of their work using text commands on a Command Line Interface (CLI). Today, CLIs are alive and well, but due to their steep learning curve they tend to be used mostly by seasoned programmers and developers or those with a computer science background.

You don’t need to know how to use the command line in order to learn a programming language like Python.

That said, intermediates like myself are waking up to the power and flexibility that a bit of command line knowledge affords. Yes, the learning curve is steep, but you can get by knowing only a few commands. And…

IMPORTANT NOTE

This is not a complete command line tutorial but a ‘first-contact’ command line experience walkthrough. If you already know your way around the command line and you just want to learn how to have your fortune told by a rainbow cow, skip to the end.

If you are serious about learning the command line, here are some excellent resources:

  • Bash beginners guide

  • Advanced Bash scripting guide

  • Learn the Linux command line

  • Linux survival

  • A to Z of the Linux command line

  • Top websites and books to transform you into a Linux command line hero

Basics¶

To unlock the power of the command line you will need to launch a terminal, sometimes referred to as a shell, or even less appropriately, a console. To avoid confusion, a terminal is a program that provides a textual input and output environment, a shell is a program that runs in the background and exposes the operating system’s services at the command line interface, and a console typically implies a physical object (e.g., a gaming console or a control panel). Nevertheless, these words are often used interchangeably for something that looks like this:

Shown above is an instance of the macOS Terminal.app after having entered a few simple commands. The terminal is running a Z shell (zsh) in the background, which is now the default shell on macOS. However, there are many different types of shell—it all depends on which operating system you are using and whether you have chosen one specifically. Windows has the Command shell and PowerShell, which we will not be focusing on here. Unix-like operating systems such as Ubuntu and macOS support even more types of shell. These include:

  • C shell (csh)

  • Bourne shell (sh)

  • GNU-Bourne-Again shell (bash)

  • KornShell (ksh)

  • Tee-see-shell (tcsh)

  • Debian-Almquist-shell (dash)

  • Friendly-interactive-shell (fish)

Admittedly, this is confusing, but you need not despair. Unix shells all function in a very similar way at a fundamental level, and you should be able to follow this tutorial using any non-Windows shell environment. Most likely this will be bash or zsh.

If you want to complete this tutorial on a Windows machine and you are running Windows 10 or above, you can install the Windows Subsytem for Linux. In brief (but do your own research first), enter wsl --install in a PowerShell, wait for the installation to complete, restart your computer, go to the Microsoft Store, search ‘Linux’, install a Linux distribution (e.g., Ubuntu), and you can then click on the shortcut for whichever distribution you just installed and launch the terminal application.

Start a terminal¶

The first step to learning the command line is launching a terminal application. On macOS, it’s called Terminal.app and you you can find it in the Applications folder, search for it using Cmd-Space, or look for it in the Launchpad. On Linux, depending on your distribution, it could be called Terminal, Terminal Emulator, Terminator, or something like that. Either way, look for an application that sounds like terminal.

After launching the terminal application, type echo $SHELL and press Enter to find out what shell program you are running. This will probably be bash or zsh.

First shell commands¶

As noted previously, knowing just a few commands is enough to get by at the command line. The table below displays some of the most ubiquitous shell commands, and if you can learn how to use these you will be off to a very good start.

Command

Description

pwd

Show the path of the current working directory

ls

LiSt files and directories in current directory

cd

Change directory

touch

Create a new file

mkdir

Create a new directory

rm

Remove a file or directory

cp

Copy a file or directory

mv

Move or rename a file or directory

echo

Print text to the standard output

cat

Concatenate / display files

more

Display contents of a file, starting at the top and letting the user scroll down.

less

Display contents of a file in an even more interactive way.

head

Display the first part of a file.

tail

Display the last part of a file.

man

Display documentation about a command

Let’s dive in. Type each of the following commands (highlighted in gray) in order and then press Enter.

  1. pwd - Print out the path of the current working directory (the folder that you are currently inside), which is likely to be your home folder

  2. mkdir tutorial - Make a new directory for this tutorial

  3. cd tutorial - Change to the tutorial directory that you just created

  4. pwd - Confirm that you are now inside the new tutorial directory

  5. touch README.txt - Create an empty text file called README.txt

  6. echo "This folder contains tutorial stuff." >> README.txt - Add some text to README.txt

  7. cat README.txt - Display the text from README.txt

  8. touch file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt - Create some empty text files

  9. ls - List the contents of the current working directory

  10. echo "Shall I compare thee to a summer's day?" >> file1.txt - Add some text to the new files

  11. echo "Thou art more lovely and more temperate." >> file2.txt

  12. echo "Rough winds do shake the darling buds of May," >> file3.txt

  13. echo "And summer's lease hath all too short a date." >> file4.txt

  14. cat file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt - Concatenate and print the lines from each file

  15. mkdir poetry - Make a new directory called poetry

  16. cat file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt >> ./poetry/sonnet18.txt - Concatenate the lines and save as a new file in poetry

  17. rm file1.txt file2.txt file3.txt file4.txt - Remove (delete) these files

  18. cd poetry - Change to new poetry folder

  19. say -f sonnet18.txt - Speak the poem aloud (may only work on macOS)

When you have finished, your terminal should look something like this.

In this little exercise, you used common shell commands to make directories and to create and process some text files. Now it is time to dive deeper and learn more about each of these commands using man.

First, type man pwd to display the manual pages for the pwd command. When you are finished reading, press q to exit the manual pages. Repeat this process for all of the commands used above.

You will see that most commands have different options that can be used to alter how the command works. Man pages are often boring and abstruse, but ultimately they contain all of the information you need to use a command correctly.

Installation¶

macOS¶

The easiest way to complete installation on macOS is via the Homebrew package manager. To install Homebrew, open a terminal and enter the following command:

/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"

When the installation is complete, you can then type the following command to install the packages:

brew install fortune cowsay lolcat

fortune¶

The fortune program prints out a random epigram from a database. Run man fortune to learn more.

[16]:

!cowsay -f k9 hello

cowsay: Could not find k9 cowfile!

[9]:

!fortune

If Dr. Seuss Were a Technical Writer.....

Here's an easy game to play.
Here's an easy thing to say:

If a packet hits a pocket on a socket on a port,
And the bus is interrupted as a very last resort,
And the address of the memory makes your floppy disk abort,
Then the socket packet pocket has an error to report!

If your cursor finds a menu item followed by a dash,
And the double-clicking icon puts your window in the trash,
And your data is corrupted 'cause the index doesn't hash,
then your situation's hopeless, and your system's gonna crash!

You can't say this?  What a shame, sir!
We'll find you another game, sir.

If the label on the cable on the table at your house,
Says the network is connected to the button on your mouse,
But your packets want to tunnel on another protocol,
That's repeatedly rejected by the printer down the hall,
And your screen is all distorted by the side effects of gauss,
So your icons in the window are as wavy as a souse,
Then you may as well reboot and go out with a bang,
'Cause as sure as I'm a poet, the sucker's gonna hang!

When the copy of your floppy's getting sloppy on the disk,

Quickly turn off the computer and be sure to tell your mom!

cowsay¶

cowsay prints text inside a speech bubble coming from a cow.

[19]:

!cowsay "Moo"

 _____
< Moo >
 -----
        \   ^__^
         \  (oo)\_______
            (__)\       )\/\
                ||----w |
                ||     ||

lolcat¶

lolcat is like the cat command, only it prints colorful text.

[5]:

!echo "The sun does arise and make happy the skies" | lolcat

The sun does arise and make happy the skies

Putting it all together¶

A cool thing about these packages is that the output of one can be ‘piped’ to another. This is achieved using the | operator. This effectively means we can have our fortune told by a rainbow colored cow. It may not be to everyone’s taste, but personally I like to see this every time I start up the command line.

[107]:

!fortune | cowsay | lolcat

 _____________________________________ 
/ There is no security on this earth. \
| There is only opportunity.          |
|                                     |
\ -- General Douglas MacArthur        /
 ------------------------------------- 
        \   ^__^
         \  (oo)\_______
            (__)\       )\/\
                ||----w |
                ||     ||

How about a lolcat fortune for every cowfile? We can list all available cowfiles using the -l option, and thanks to excellent shell integration of Jupyter notebooks we can capture the output into a Python variable.

[11]:

cowfiles = !cowsay -l
cowfiles

[11]:

['Cow files in /opt/homebrew/Cellar/cowsay/3.04_1/share/cows:',
 'beavis.zen blowfish bong bud-frogs bunny cheese cower daemon default dragon',
 'dragon-and-cow elephant elephant-in-snake eyes flaming-sheep ghostbusters',

We just want a list of all possible options so let’s do a bit of processing

[110]:

cowfiles = [c.split(' ') for c in cowfiles[1:]]  # First line is not an option
cowfiles = [c for sublist in cowfiles for c in sublist]  # Flatten the list
print(cowfiles, '\n')  # This is our list of cowfiles

['bud-frogs', 'bunny', 'cheese', 'cower', 'daemon', 'default', 'dragon', 'dragon-and-cow', 'elephant', 'elephant-in-snake', 'eyes', 'flaming-sheep', 'ghostbusters', 'head-in', 'hellokitty', 'kiss', 'kitty', 'koala', 'kosh', 'luke-koala', 'meow', 'milk', 'moofasa', 'moose', 'mutilated', 'ren', 'satanic', 'sheep', 'skeleton', 'small', 'stegosaurus', 'stimpy', 'supermilker', 'surgery', 'three-eyes', 'turkey', 'turtle', 'tux', 'udder', 'vader', 'vader-koala', 'www']

Great, now let’s iterate over the cowfiles and execute a shell command for each of them. Again, because Jupyter is closely integrated with the shell, we can affix the loop variable with a dollar sign to pass in the cowfile option when executing the system command.

[13]:

for c in cowfiles:
    print(f'~~~ {c} ~~~')
    !fortune | cowsay -f $c | lolcat
